node.text: Over 100,000 Americans are currently hospitalized with Covid-19, and over 1,000 people are dying every day. These are people from all walks of life—rich and poor, white collar and blue collar, old and young. But according to an estimate from the Kaiser Family Foundation, over 98% of them have one thing in common: despite the ready availability of Covid vaccines, they chose not to get them.

node.text: It’s estimated that there are over 27 million Indigenous people living on the world’s coastlines. For these coastal communities, the ocean has been vital to their culture and survival for thousands of years. But global seafood consumption is rising, fueling a multibillion-dollar commercial fishing industry. And experts warn that, in some places, these commercial vessels are catching more fish than the ocean can provide, threatening sea life and the very people who rely on the ocean the most. Tap the link in bio to watch the full video.

node.title: How Overfishing Robs Coastal Indigenous Communities Of Their Livelihoods

node.text: As 'Bridgerton's Lady Whistledown would say: “The social season is upon us.” And, this fall, to celebrate the still-going-strong 'Bridgerton' craze with proper pomp and circumstance, Estancia La Jolla Hotel and Spa in California is planning a Halloween bash fit for royals on its beautifully landscaped grounds. Beginning at 5 p.m. on Oct. 31, the Bridgerton Masquerade Halloween Soirée will take place in Estancia La Jolla’s “Secret Garden.” Tickets are $150. Gin cocktails and bubbles will be flowing, unlimited bites abound and live entertainment will set the soundtrack. Oh, and cue the Regency-era costumes that are sure to stun. 'Bridgerton' became one of Netflix’s biggest hits of all time, with 82 million households watching Shonda Rhimes’ British period piece in the first month that it streamed. With coronavirus restrictions still in place, the regency romance with Jane Austen-like storytelling and soapy drama was a stay-at-home fix—a little steam to heat up the long, cold winter. But now as vaccination rates increase and people ease back into travel (perhaps not ready to hop the pond just yet), hotels like Estancia La Jolla are getting creative with their royal programming and offering some life-imitates-art experiences. node.text: Spring Health notched a $190 million series C at a $2 billion valuation, making CEO April Koh the youngest woman to run a unicorn. Convinced that there had to be a better way to match patients to the best treatments, Koh teamed up with Adam Chekroud, a Ph.D student at Yale who in 2016 published peer-reviewed research on the ways that machine learning could help match patients to the best care providers for their needs. That same year, Koh and Chekroud founded Spring Health, a platform that would use “precision mental healthcare” to solve the struggle of finding the right course of mental health treatment. Five years later, Koh (Spring’s CEO) and Chekroud (Spring’s president) have guided Spring to unicorn status: the company is announcing Thursday that it has secured a $190 million Series C round of funding at a $2 billion valuation. The round was led by health investor Kinnevik; insurer Guardian Life joined as a new investor, while existing investors—including Tiger Global, Rethink Impact and Work-Bench—also participated. The raise also means that Koh, 29, is now the youngest female CEO of a multi-billion dollar startup. Koh, Chekroud and their third cofounder, Abhishek Chandra, landed on the #ForbesUnder30 list in 2018. Tap the link in bio to learn more. (📸: Spring Health)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Forbes on September 19, 2021. May be an image of 2 people, people standing and text that says 'Forbes Finally. Care for the whole you. This Startup Raised $100 $100 Million To Turbocharge Women's Health'.

node.text: Around 1 in 10 women in the United States has polycystic ovarian syndrome, yet it took Carolyn Witte more than three years to have a doctor diagnose her with the disease—and even then she had to do a lot of the research herself. “That exposed me to the challenges of this fragmented system and how that negatively affects women,” says Witte. And her experience is not unique—it’s estimated around 50-75% of women with the disease are unaware they have it. “What would healthcare look like, work like, feel like, if it was actually designed with women at the center of it?” she wondered. “If it treated women as whole people versus parts?” Her answer to that question is Tia, a four-year-old startup that combines in-person and virtual care for women, which she cofounded with Felicity Yost. The New York-based company announced a $100 million Series B on Tuesday led by Lone Pine Capital. Existing investors including Threshold, Define Ventures and Torch Capital, among others, participated in the round, which values Tia at $600 million, according to a person familiar with the deal. Tap the link in bio for the full read. (📸: Tia)

node.text: Growing up, Ketish founder Emaan Abbass was always curious about sex and feminine wellness. But in her household, both topics were considered taboo, as was the idea of premarital sex. That’s why Abbass wished she had a brand like Ketish to turn to, to help her learn about her body and make informed choices about her sexual health. “That's what I really want to create with Ketish, not just amazing feminine and intimate wellness products, but just this platform [where] women can come, and engage and learn, and feel like [they have] the support of an entire army of women behind [them],” she explains. In 2017, when her then-boss Huda Kattan announced she would be starting Huda Beauty Angels, a business initiative to invest in female-founded businesses, Abbass realized her dream brand could become a reality. She pitched her idea to Kattan and after a bit of workshopping, the beauty mogul agreed to invest, making Ketish the very first HB Angels-backed brand. After that, it took about three years to bring the brand to life—Ketish just launched its first product, the Quickie, on August 12. Tap the link in bio for the full read and to check out more from The Highlight, @ForbesVetted's column dedicated to amplifying brands created for Women of Color by Women of Color. (📸: Ketish)

node.text: People notice when Jay-Z and Beyoncé go on vacation—or anywhere for that matter. And you could say that people notice just a little bit more when they vacation aboard the 450-foot-long, 67-foot-wide superyacht Flying Fox that was built by Lürssen in Germany, and costs roughly $4 million per week to charter. But then again, superyachts that are much longer than a football field get a fair amount of attention as well. Superyacht designer Espen Oeino has designed an elegant yacht exterior that looks sleek in spite of her massive size. The balance and proportion of the exterior allows for generous deck space that offers a range of options for Jay-Z, Beyoncé and their guests to enjoy. Numerous terraces and platforms open out over the water to provide fantastic access to the water. Every other exterior element, from sun decks and open entertainment areas to more shaded and intimate spaces, has been designed to provide the highest level of luxury. Tap the link in bio for more details. (📸: Imperial)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Forbes on September 18, 2021. May be an image of 3 people, people sitting and text that says 'Forbes Canva Raises At $40 Billion Valuation-Its Founders Are Pledging Away Most Of Their Wealth'.

node.text: Canva is now one of the world’s most valuable startups after raising $200 million in new funding at a $40 billion valuation. The round, led by T. Rowe Price with Franklin Templeton, Sequoia, Bessemer Venture Partners, Greenoaks Capital, Dragoneer, Blackbird, Felicis and AirTree all participating, more than doubles the Australian design software company’s valuation in five months. Canva’s already on a level few startups have reached—not just for a valuation second only to Stripe on the Forbes Cloud 100 list of top private cloud companies. Long profitable and cash-flow positive, Canva continues to more than double in sales, the company says, on pace to reach a $1 billion annualized revenue run-rate by December 2021, the “vast majority” of that recurring subscription revenue. “Moving in the right direction,” cofounder and CEO Melanie Perkins says matter-of-factly. Canva defied early skepticism to emerge as one of the world’s most popular and fastest-growing software tools, putting Perkins, a #ForbesUnder30 alum, on the cover of the magazine in December 2019. Started in 2012 by Perkins, now-husband Cliff Obrecht and Cameron Adams, Canva launched the following year as a tool to help anyone design, from better-looking resumes to menus, business cards and other graphic assets. Tap the link in bio for the full read. (📸: Canva)

node.text: As expected, on September 14, Apple CEO Tim Cook and his team took to the Internet to tout this year’s lineup of new iPhones, Apple Watches, iPads and related services. While there were a few surprises, one thing was made clear—this year’s product upgrades are some of the best ever. The latest lineup of Apple iPhones includes the iPhone 13, iPhone 13 Mini, iPhone 13 Pro and iPhone 13 Pro Max. Available in an assortment of new casing colors, the latest iPhones offer a longer battery life, improved displays, upgraded camera systems and operate using Apple’s new A15 Bionic processor chip. Both the front- and rear-facing cameras retain their 12MP resolution, but utilize other new technologies to give these cameras a huge boost in performance whether you’re shooting still images or 4K HD video at up to 60 frames-per-second. Tap the link in bio to read about the new Apple Watch Series 7 and Apple’s affordable new iPad. Plus, follow @forbesvetted for more shopping news! (📸: Apple)

node.text: Over 100,000 Americans are currently hospitalized with Covid-19, and over 1,000 people are dying every day. These are people from all walks of life—rich and poor, white collar and blue collar, old and young. But according to an estimate from the Kaiser Family Foundation, over 98% of them have one thing in common: despite the ready availability of Covid vaccines, they chose not to get them.
